03413nam a22004455i 9780773566422DE-B159720230529101353.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19971997xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735664227 a10.1515/97807735664222doi  a(DE-B1597)656963  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLB45bS596 1997eb 7aEDU0030002bisacsh04a306.431 aSolway, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLying about the Wolf :bEssays in Culture and Education /cDavid Solway. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1997] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on the Text -- tNote on Notes -- tIntroduction -- tGrammatical Fictions -- tDead Teachers Society -- tBalnibarbian Architecture -- tThe Anecdotal Function -- tWhat About Food? -- tScript and Nondescript -- tThe Bipolar Paradigm -- tCharlie Don’t Surf -- tTeaching Down or Learning Up -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSolway explains that the current generation of students, raised in a nonhistorical and iconic environment, do not live in time as an emergent, continuous medium in which the complexities of experience are parsed and organized. Their psychological world is largely devoid of syntax - of causal, differential, and temporal relations between events. The result is precisely what we see about us: a cultural world characterized by a vast subpopulation of young (and not so young) people for whom the past is an unsubstantiated rumour and the future an unacknowledged responsibility. Solway claims that contemporary educators have become cultural speculators who disregard a basic truth about how the mind develops: that it needs to be grounded in reality and time. In education, as in almost every other cultural institution, the sense of reality and the dynamic of time have "virtually" disappeared, leading to the deep disconnectedness we experience on every level of "human grammar," from the organization of the community to the organization of the sentence. Lying about the Wolf is not only an exploration of current pedagogical issues but also, and perhaps primarily, a cultural analysis for which the subject of education provides a focus. Solway argues that we cannot hope to solve the educational problem unless we are prepared to deal with the larger cultural predicament.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aEDUCATION / Aims & Objectives.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356642240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773566422423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773566422/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles